http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/05/business/media/05decency.html?ex=1338696000&en=d31a8d498dfcd90a&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss F.C.C. Rebuffed by Court on Indecency Fines - New York Times F.C.C. Rebuffed by Court on Indecency Fines June 5, 2007 WASHINGTON, June 4 — If President Bush and Vice President Cheney can use vulgar language, then the government cannot punish others for doing the same thing on television. Skip to next paragraph Decision by the U.S. Court of Appeals (pdf) That, in essence, was the decision today when a federal appeals court struck down the government policy of fining stations and networks that broadcast programs with profanity. The decision, by a divided panel of the United States Court of Appeals for the Second Circuit in New York, was a sharp rebuke for the and for the Bush administration. It was a major victory in a legal battle being waged by the four television networks — Fox, , NBC and ABC — that had filed the case. Beginning with its indecency finding in a case against NBC for an obscenity uttered by the during the Golden Globes ceremony in 2003, President Bush’s Republican and Democratic appointees to the commission have imposed a tougher indecency policy by punishing any station that used what was known as a “fleeting expletive,” or blurted profanity. Reversing decades of more lenient policy, the commission had found that the mere utterance of profane words implied sexual or excretory acts and therefore violated the indecency rules. But in striking down the commission’s interpretation, the appeals court noted that “in recent times even the top leaders of our government has used variants of these expletives in a manner that no reasonable person would believe referenced sexual or excretory organs or activities.” Adopting an argument made by lawyers for NBC, the court then cited examples in which Mr. Bush and Mr. Cheney had used language that would be penalized under the policy. Mr. Bush was caught on videotape last July using a common vulgarity that the commission finds objectionable in a conversation with Prime Minister . And three years ago, Mr. Cheney was widely reported to have muttered a profane comment to , a Vermont Democrat, on the floor of the “We find that the F.C.C.’s new policy regarding ‘fleeting expletives’ fails to provide a reasoned analysis justifying its departure from the agency’s established practice,” said the court. Although the court struck down the policy on statutory grounds, it also said that it had serious broader constitutional problems with the commission’s attempt to regulate the language of television programs. “We are skeptical that the commission can provide a reasoned explanation for its ‘fleeting expletive’ regime that would pass constitutional muster,” said the court in an opinion written by Judge Rosemary S. Pooler and joined by Judge Peter W. Hall. “We question whether the F.C.C.’s indecency test can survive First Amendment scrutiny.” While the court sent the case back to the commission to rewrite its policy, it said that it was “doubtful” that the agency would be able to “adequately respond to the constitutional and statutory challenges raised by the networks.” The case decided today, Fox et al. v. Federal Communications Commission, has been closely watched by the television industry and its critics for their broad implications on television programming — as has a case now before a federal appeals court in Philadelphia involving the malfunctioning wardrobe of at the 2005 Super Bowl. Neither cable nor satellite television face the same indecency rules even though they cover about 85 percent of homes. And as the Bush administration’s appointees have taken a tougher view on indecency, the industry has waged a counter-campaign in the courts. The case decided today involved findings against the networks for comments by Cher and Nicole Richie on the Billboard Music Awards, the use of expletives on “N.Y.P.D. Blue,” and a comment on “The Early Show” by a contestant on CBS’s reality show “Survivor.” Next Article in Business (1 of 20) &#x00bb; Need Erred in Firing Reporter Who Cursed, Arbitrator Says Senate Backs Increase in Fine for Indecency 'Sopranos' Undergoes Cosmetic Surgery for Basic Cable THE TV WATCH; As Stern Ranted, Letterman Debated Next Article in Business (1 of 20) &#x00bb; MOST POPULAR - BUSINESS Your Money: More Advice Graduates Don&#8217;t Want to Hear Google Keeps Tweaking Its Search Engine Your Money: The 6 Percent Solution: Skip Real Estate Agents Advertising: Publishers Creating Their Own In-House Ad Agencies Career Couch: For the Chronically Late, It&#8217;s Not a Power Trip Everybody Talks About the Weather; All of a Sudden, It&#8217;s Controversial Ping: Genius and Misfit Aren&#8217;t Synonyms, or Are They? A Theme Song for Clinton: &#8216;I&#8217;m a Believer&#8217; vs. &#8216;Cold as Ice&#8217; A Hot-Selling Weapon, an Inviting Target Your Money: Advice to All You Graduates: Let&#39;s Start With That Daily Latte . . . Go Fiction and Lou Dobbs Lawmakers Push for Big Subsidies for Coal Process Dow Jones Says It Will Consider Options for Sale Grandma Cooks, They Deliver How the Bancrofts Decided to Talk With Murdoch Is Wal-Mart Too Cheap for Its Own Good? Now, Spitzer Is Warming to Wall St. Overbooking, Bumped Fliers and No Plan B Go the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuchee Bluegrass Festival? Tell him where to go in Tennessee and Kentucky Media & Advertising &#x00bb; The Lede: Paris Hilton Reports to Prison ‘Grey Gardens’ Provides the Role of a Life Home Fires: Iraq Veterans Return All of a Sudden, the Weather Is Controversial The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/03/magazine/03wwln-consumed-t.html Wines - Alcoholic Beverages - Alcohol - Consumed - Rob Walker - New York Times June 3, 2007 Skip to next paragraph Illustration by Leif Parsons Consumer sophistication is on the rise. Just look at what we drink. Not coffee from a can or mass-market beer, but complex lattes and fine pinot noir. When there is a great enough thirst for sophistication (or anything else), something becomes inevitable: a chain of relevant franchises. Or in the case of wine, a couple of them: one recent list of fast-growing franchises included both Vino 100 (with about 60 locations open) and WineStyles (about 110 locations). In both instances, the guiding mission is to present wine to consumers in a manner that’s unpretentious and demystified — not so, you know, sophisticated. Each chain emphasizes a desnobbed lexicon for wine discussion, a heavily edited selection of relatively low-priced bottles and an emphasis on the shop as a location for events and socializing. WineStyles, which began franchising in 2004, sorts its offerings on shelves not by country of origin or grape varietal but by way of a “style system” that boils down to eight “flavor profile” words, like “crisp” “silky” and “bold.” This is an easier system for a consumer to relate to, according to Robert Spuck, the C.E.O. of WineStyles. Similarly, a typical WineStyles store carries about 160 wines, because, he argues, that’s as much as the shopper wants to deal with. Many of the selections at any given WineStyles store are actually proprietary: the chain works with wineries to produce batches that are under labels, like Killer Bee, that the chain owns. This means you “don’t have to pay for all that branding and everything” that’s built into the price of some other wines, Spuck says. New house labels are introduced all the time to meet the wine consumer’s thirst for variety. But the strategy also happens to play to many a wine buyer’s tendency to buy some labels over and over — long after the actual vintage he first enjoyed has been quaffed (as oenephiles like to say) out of existence. At Vino 100, the organizing principle is suggested by the name: a hundred wines priced at $25 or less. Employees are trained to use the company’s “vino speak,” which avoids words like “tannin” or “sulfates” in favor of continuums like dry versus fruity and light versus heavy, and food pairings. “It’s talking English,” says Gary Blumenthal, the founder. Blumenthal is also the president of Tinder Box, a chain of 150 or so cigar stores, and he aims to replicate the system he says has worked well for that chain, keeping track of customers’ purchases, likes and dislikes to guide new suggestions. “People ask me all the time, ‘What’s a good cigar?’ ” he says. “I tell them it’s the one you like.” It’s the same with wine, he says: “Somebody is involved with cigars or wine because they want to be. They want it to be fun. They don’t want it to be stressful, they don’t want to feel stupid and they don’t want to feel cheap.” It’s safe to say that these chains aim to be something like the of wine. Starbucks, after all, is an icon of the new and more sophisticated America. You can argue that Starbucks has achieved its place by fancying up a commodity (coffee) or by making the once-unusual latte into something as easily obtainable as a Whopper. But both Spuck and Blumenthal stress a different Starbucks-like quality: the retail establishment as gathering place. Vino 100 franchises hold scores of events with names like Wining Women. WineStyles shops all have clubs, some with hundreds of members. Both have put a great deal of effort into inviting store design. In a way, the actual wine sounds less important than the context in which it’s purchased. “That’s what people in our demographic enjoy doing,” Spuck says. “Meeting other people who are congruent with their personality and with income and probably education background. We give them a meeting place, and wine happens to be the focal point.” Or rather, lots of meeting places. These chains have not invented the idea of the comfortable, neighborhood wine shop, which has been around for a long time. One pertinent example is Best Cellars, which opened in Manhattan in 1996 with a welcoming design, a 100-bottle selection and an eight-category flavor-profile system — “fresh,” “juicy,” “big,” etc. (It now has eight locations.) Then again, Starbucks did not invent the cafe. The key to chains in the new sophisticated America is the same as ever: not creating a special place but replicating it, as far and wide as possible. Next Article in Magazine (11 of 16) &#x00bb; Need OF THE TIMES; Summer Breezes in, Sipping Barbera LONG ISLAND VINES; A Smooth and Meaty Malbec Napa Valley? Bordeaux? No, but Still Wine Country Retail Stores and Trade Next Article in Magazine (11 of 16) &#x00bb; Follow the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuchee Bluegrass Festival? Tell him where to go in Tennessee and Kentucky Sultans of Swat Commemorative Media & Advertising &#x00bb; The Lede: Paris Hilton Reports to Prison ‘Grey Gardens’ Provides the Role of a Life Home Fires: Iraq Veterans Return All of a Sudden, the Weather Is Controversial The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/04/business/04avaya.html?ex=1338609600&en=2ecea4d7ac140197&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss Phone Equipment Manufacturer May Be Sold - New York Times Phone Equipment Manufacturer May Be Sold MICHAEL J. de la MERCED Published: June 4, 2007 was near a deal last night to sell itself to Silver Lake Partners and the Texas Pacific Group for more than $8 billion in the latest buyout in the telecommunications industry, according to people briefed on the sale. The two private equity firms appear to have bested a rival bid from and a deal may be announced as early as today, those people said. But they cautioned that the talks were ongoing and that Nortel could field a higher 11th-hour bid. The firms are expected to pay about $17 per share, the people said. Avaya’s shares closed Friday at $16.08. Speculation about a buyout first arose two weeks ago, when the company unexpectedly postponed a meeting with analysts without offering an explanation or setting a new date. An Avaya spokeswoman would not comment. Avaya, which was once a division of Lucent Technologies and before that, is one of the nation’s top makers of phone equipment, rivaling in providing Internet-based communications to corporations. Much of its business focuses on upgrading companies to voice networks that can also offer video and data services. Avaya draws almost a third of its revenue from its long-term maintenance contracts, though the company has warned that as those agreements expire, its customers have the leverage to demand lower fees. The company, which was spun off from Lucent in October 2000, suffered in 2002 as the dot-com bubble burst. But its financial health has rebounded so strongly that a analyst recently described Avaya as an ideal buyout candidate. In its fiscal year ended Sept. 30, 2006, the company reported net profit of $201 million on revenue of $5.12 billion, and it is virtually debt-free. The company, based in Basking Ridge, N.J., has about 20,000 employees. The move comes amid heavy deal-making in the telecommunications sector. Last month, , the wireless service provider, agreed to a $27.5 billion buyout by Texas Pacific and a unit of Analysts have predicted consolidation in the telecommunications equipment sector. Mergers among phone companies have amplified their size and purchasing power, while low-cost Asian companies have squeezed the profits of their Western counterparts. Last year, Alcatel and Lucent agreed to merge in an $11.6 billion deal, which many analysts say forced players like Avaya and Nortel to ally to stay competitive. Some analysts had seen an Avaya-Nortel pairing as a good fit. But the companies’ overlap in product offerings make integration difficult, analysts said. Next Article in Business (13 of 20) &#x00bb; Need Is Said to Be Exploring a Sale of All or Some of Itself Next Article in Business (13 of 20) &#x00bb; MOST POPULAR - BUSINESS Your Money: More Advice Graduates Don&#8217;t Want to Hear Google Keeps Tweaking Its Search Engine Your Money: The 6 Percent Solution: Skip Real Estate Agents Advertising: Publishers Creating Their Own In-House Ad Agencies Career Couch: For the Chronically Late, It&#8217;s Not a Power Trip Everybody Talks About the Weather; All of a Sudden, It&#8217;s Controversial Ping: Genius and Misfit Aren&#8217;t Synonyms, or Are They? A Theme Song for Clinton: &#8216;I&#8217;m a Believer&#8217; vs. &#8216;Cold as Ice&#8217; A Hot-Selling Weapon, an Inviting Target Your Money: Advice to All You Graduates: Let&#39;s Start With That Daily Latte . . . Go Fiction and Lou Dobbs Lawmakers Push for Big Subsidies for Coal Process Dow Jones Says It Will Consider Options for Sale Grandma Cooks, They Deliver How the Bancrofts Decided to Talk With Murdoch Is Wal-Mart Too Cheap for Its Own Good? Now, Spitzer Is Warming to Wall St. Overbooking, Bumped Fliers and No Plan B Go the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuchee Blue