http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/04/business/worldbusiness/04merge.html?ex=1338609600&en=fb23c00a36d4a521&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss Qiagen to Buy Digene, Maker of Tests for Cancer-Causing Virus - New York Times Qiagen to Buy Digene, Maker of Tests for Cancer-Causing Virus June 4, 2007 , a Dutch maker of tools for gene research, has agreed to buy the for $1.6 billion in shares and cash to gain tests for a virus that causes cervical Digene investors will get $61.25 a share, 37 percent more than Friday’s closing price. Digene, based in Gaithersburg, Md., produces the only test for that has been approved in Europe and the United States, Qiagen said yesterday. The two companies have worked together for more than 10 years. The human papilloma virus, or H.P.V., is linked to about 70 percent of cervical cancer cases. have developed vaccines for the illness, which is the second-most-common cancer among women after , and kills 250,000 women a year. The market for an H.P.V. test is worth more than $1 billion, the companies said. The purchase gives Qiagen “instantaneous market and technology leadership” in molecular diagnostics and will be “a catalyst for growth,” Peer M. Schatz, chief executive of Qiagen, said. Digene’s H.P.V. test is often done in labs that also use Qiagen products, the companies said. Qiagen sells sample and testing technologies used to research , RNA and proteins. The products are used by drug makers, academic research labs and medical clinics. The purchase will add as much as $60 million to sales in the fourth quarter and between $260 million and $270 million to revenue next year, Qiagen said. The deal will add as much as 4 cents to adjusted earnings a share next year and will be “significantly accretive” thereafter. Pretax cost savings will be $35 million to $45 million a year. The company does not expect significant changes in the work force, Mr. Schatz. The company said that it expected total sales to increase to more than $800 million next year. On Feb. 13, Qiagen forecast revenue for this year of as much as $535 million. Digene shareholders can choose between the cash offer or 3.545 of Qiagen’s stock for each of their shares. Qiagen expects Digene shareholders to own about 22 percent of its stock on a fully diluted basis after the transaction. The transaction, which is supported by both boards, is expected to be completed before the end of September. Mr. Schatz will remain chief executive, and Roland Sackers of Qiagen will remain chief financial officer. Daryl J. Faulkner, Digene’s chief executive, will serve as co-head of the steering committee overseeing the integration. The company’s United States headquarters will be in Maryland. Qiagen now has operations in Valencia, Calif. Next Article in Business (14 of 20) &#x00bb; Need Papilloma Virus (HPV) Mergers, Acquisitions and Divestitures Next Article in Business (14 of 20) &#x00bb; MOST POPULAR - BUSINESS Your Money: More Advice Graduates Don&#8217;t Want to Hear Google Keeps Tweaking Its Search Engine Your Money: The 6 Percent Solution: Skip Real Estate Agents Advertising: Publishers Creating Their Own In-House Ad Agencies Career Couch: For the Chronically Late, It&#8217;s Not a Power Trip Everybody Talks About the Weather; All of a Sudden, It&#8217;s Controversial Ping: Genius and Misfit Aren&#8217;t Synonyms, or Are They? A Theme Song for Clinton: &#8216;I&#8217;m a Believer&#8217; vs. &#8216;Cold as Ice&#8217; A Hot-Selling Weapon, an Inviting Target Your Money: Advice to All You Graduates: Let&#39;s Start With That Daily Latte . . . Go Fiction and Lou Dobbs Lawmakers Push for Big Subsidies for Coal Process Dow Jones Says It Will Consider Options for Sale Grandma Cooks, They Deliver How the Bancrofts Decided to Talk With Murdoch Is Wal-Mart Too Cheap for Its Own Good? Now, Spitzer Is Warming to Wall St. Overbooking, Bumped Fliers and No Plan B Go the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuc