http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/05/business/05bizcourt.html Supreme Court Rules in Favor of Insurance Companies - New York Times Supreme Court Rules in Favor of Insurance Companies THE ASSOCIATED PRESS Published: June 5, 2007 WASHINGTON, June 4 (AP) — The Supreme Court sided with two insurance companies Monday in a case involving alleged violations of the Fair Credit Reporting Act. The law requires insurance companies and other businesses to notify customers who are charged more because of their credit ratings. In a unanimous decision, the justices said the Geico General Insurance Company did not violate the law and that Safeco might have, but did not do so recklessly. The insurance industry said a decision against it could have subjected companies to billions of dollars in punitive damages for failing to notify customers. To find liability, a company’s conduct must be more than “merely careless,” wrote Justice David Souter. Justice Souter said that a company’s conduct must entail an unjustifiably high risk of harm that is either known to a company or is so obvious that it should have been known. Overturning an appeals court decision, the Supreme Court adopted a notification requirement favored by the industry. The standard limits the circumstances in which customers must be told their premiums are higher because of their credit ratings. Thirteen state insurance commissioners said that a lower threshhold for proving liability, adopted by the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit in San Francisco, would motivate compliance with the law. The appeals court and lawyers for consumers said they must be notified any time they pay more than the lowest rate available to customers with the very best credit scores. “Geico has the better position,” the Supreme Court said. Geico did not owe a prospective customer such notification, the court said. The company had offered him a rate that was the one he would have received if his credit score had not been taken into account. Safeco did not notify two of its customers because it thought the law did not apply to initial applications, a mistake that left the company in violation of the law. “The company was not reckless in falling down on its duty,” Justice Souter wrote. Under a more expansive notification standard, Safeco would be required to send adverse action notices to 80 percent of the company’s new customers, Maureen Mahoney, a lawyer defending the two companies, said at arguments in the Supreme Court in January. At Geico, just 10 percent of new customers qualify for the top tier of credit, Ms. Mahoney added. Next Article in Business (4 of 20) &#x00bb; Need Show Their Doubts On State Law On Holocaust Court May Review Health Insurance Case Policyholders Push for Owners' Rights as More Insurers Go Public New Bill on Patients' Rights Is Both Hailed and Criticized Next Article in Business (4 of 20) &#x00bb; Follow the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuchee Bluegrass Festival? Tell him where to go in Tennessee and Kentucky George Washington Bronze Portrait Bust Media & Advertising &#x00bb; The Lede: Paris Hilton Reports to Prison ‘Grey Gardens’ Provides the Role of a Life Home Fires: Iraq Veterans Return All of a Sudden, the Weather Is Controversial The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/04/business/worldbusiness/04cnd-chinastox.html Chinese Stocks Fall After Government Increases Taxes - New York Times Chinese Stocks Fall After Government Increases Taxes June 4, 2007 SHANGHAI, June 4 — China’s stock market tumbled again today in one of the biggest sell-offs in years. It followed the government’s move last week to impose higher taxes on stock trades. Skip to next paragraph Stock investors looked at the price monitor at a securities company in Shanghai, China. The New York Times The sell-off today in Shanghai was one of the largest declines in a decade, and was nearly comparable to the sharp drop in February this year when the Shanghai Composite fell 9.9 percent after a phenomenal rise. The benchmark Shanghai Stock Exchange fell 330 points, or 8.3 percent, to close today at 3,670.40. The country’s other major index, the Shenzhen Composite, dropped 7.9 percent to close at 1,039.89. Shares in other parts of Asia fared better, including Tokyo and Hong Kong, where stock prices rose modestly. Analysts and economists have been warning for months about a bubble building in the Chinese stock market. But prices have continued to soar on unprecedented demand for stocks, fueled by the opening of hundreds of thousands of new share accounts every day. The government has repeatedly warned investors about the risks of a downturn, and even moved to calm the markets. Most downturns have been only temporary. Now, however, shares have fallen in what looks like a more permanent correction since the government announced last Wednesday that it would raise its stamp duty tax to 0.3 percent from 0.1 percent. Frank Song, director of the center for Chinese Financial Research at Hong Kong University, said: “This is somewhat expected. Last week’s policy change is a strong signal that the government will no longer tolerate this rising bubble.” The government had said earlier that it had no plans to increase the stamp duty. But it then reversed course and announced an immediate implementation. Shares tumbled 6.5 percent last Wednesday, then bounced back on Thursday before falling again on Friday. Today’s fall saw a massive downturn in prices that peeled back weeks of huge gains and left the benchmark Shanghai Composite down 15.3 percent from its high of 4,334.92 over just three sessions. More than half of the stocks in the CSI 300 plunged by the 10 percent daily limit. “It is not clear whether the market will continue to decline,” Mr. Song said. “It may depend on whether investors will continue to open new accounts.” Concern that the government would raise taxes again on share trading was heightened Friday after figures showed the stamp duty increase failed to deter investors from opening accounts. More than 400,000 brokerage accounts were set up on May 30, exceeding this quarter’s daily average of about 300,000, official figures showed. The number of accounts last week topped 100 million for the first time. Few analysts are forecasting a bear market, but many had been warning of more government measures and a sharp downturn. There are fears, however, among analysts and the government that a severe correction in prices could lead to a rout, creating widespread anger and perhaps even unrest in China. When the government reversed course last week and imposed higher taxes on stock trades, investors vented their anger online and there were even reports that several government web sites, including a finance ministry site, had been hacked into and taken down for a time. Bloomberg News contributed to this report. Next Article in Business (10 of 20) &#x00bb; Get early access to articles from this Sunday's Times. Sign up for TimesSelect free for 14 days. DAYS; China&#8217;s Investors Pull Back, but U.S. Bull Is Unfazed Tax Increase Batters Chinese Stocks, but There&#8217;s Little Wider Damage Chinese Shares Plunge 6.5 Percent In a Switch, China Triples the Tax on Stock Trades Next Article in Business (10 of 20) &#x00bb;