http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/04/business/media/04nbc.html?ex=1338609600&en=32220089164f2325&ei=5088&partner=rssnyt&emc=rss NBC Names Program Executive to Head TV Studio - New York Times NBC Names Program Executive to Head TV Studio June 4, 2007 NBC Universal took another step in revamping its television entertainment operations yesterday, appointing Katherine Pope as president of its television production studio, NBC Universal Television. The move came less than a week after it hired the independent producer Ben Silverman as a co-chairman, with Marc Graboff, of the television group, with authority over both the entertainment division of the NBC network and the television studio. That appointment, which coincided with the removal of Kevin Reilly as president of NBC Entertainment, raised questions about the future of Ms. Pope, who had been the top program development executive for NBC and was one of the most highly regarded young executives at the network. But NBC Universal acted quickly to answer those questions by giving Ms. Pope authority over the studio, which is producing hit shows like “Heroes” and “The Office” for NBC and “House” for Fox. Ms. Pope, who is in her mid-30s, will succeed Angela Bromstad, who headed the studio before she stepped away from the job several months ago. Ms. Bromstad is expected to be appointed to another NBC Universal position, perhaps heading its international division in London. Ms. Pope said in a telephone interview yesterday that she expected to “hit the ground running” in her new position, speaking to writers and producers and instigating new programs as quickly as possible. She said she has been impressed by Mr. Silverman’s passion and vision. “He’s like a hurricane of energy and ideas,” she said. The studio “will take risks both monetarily and creatively,” Ms. Pope said. Asked what that might entail, she said she would encourage writers to bring new ideas and would give them latitude in carrying out those ideas. The studio hopes to commission pilots as early as this summer, she said. NBC continues to trail the other broadcast networks and needs hit programs. Ms Pope said she saw the studio as “having two clients, the writers and NBC.” Beyond the quest for a new generation of hits, Ms. Pope said she and Mr. Silverman had discussed “the larger questions of where the business is going.” That, she said, means “thinking about new ideas, new avenues of distribution and the necessity to think globally about our content.” Next Article in Business (17 of 20) &#x00bb; Need in Shake-Up, Names Outsider to a Top Position NBC Brings In Programming Help '60 Minutes' Creator Takes On Rockettes TV SPORTS; Network Shuffle Leaves N.H.L. Out in the Cold Next Article in Business (17 of 20) &#x00bb; MOST POPULAR - BUSINESS Your Money: More Advice Graduates Don&#8217;t Want to Hear Google Keeps Tweaking Its Search Engine Your Money: The 6 Percent Solution: Skip Real Estate Agents Advertising: Publishers Creating Their Own In-House Ad Agencies Career Couch: For the Chronically Late, It&#8217;s Not a Power Trip Everybody Talks About the Weather; All of a Sudden, It&#8217;s Controversial Ping: Genius and Misfit Aren&#8217;t Synonyms, or Are They? A Theme Song for Clinton: &#8216;I&#8217;m a Believer&#8217; vs. &#8216;Cold as Ice&#8217; A Hot-Selling Weapon, an Inviting Target Your Money: Advice to All You Graduates: Let&#39;s Start With That Daily Latte . . . Go Fiction and Lou Dobbs Lawmakers Push for Big Subsidies for Coal Process Dow Jones Says It Will Consider Options for Sale Grandma Cooks, They Deliver How the Bancrofts Decided to Talk With Murdoch Is Wal-Mart Too Cheap for Its Own Good? Now, Spitzer Is Warming to Wall St. Overbooking, Bumped Fliers and No Plan B Go the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuchee Bluegrass Festival? Tell him where to go in Tennessee and Kentucky Media & Advertising &#x00bb; The Lede: Paris Hilton Reports to Pr