http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/04/technology/04chip.html Specialized Software Maker Is Said to Be in Buyout Talks - New York Times Specialized Software Maker Is Said to Be in Buyout Talks MICHAEL J. de la MERCED Published: June 4, 2007 , one of the largest makers of the software used to design computer chips, is in talks with at least two buyout firms about a possible sale of the company, two people close to the matter said yesterday. The company has held talks with Kohlberg Kravis Roberts and the Blackstone Group, and other suitors may emerge, those people said. But they warned that a deal may not happen because of the complicated risks in the company's business. Other private equity firms took a look at Cadence but passed. Representatives for Blackstone, Kohlberg Kravis and Cadence declined to comment. A deal for Cadence would be one of the biggest moves by private equity firms into technology, a sector they have avoided because of its volatility and need for capital. But as buyout firms have grown bolder and more flush with cash, they may be betting that they can still wring out lucrative returns. Though both Kohlberg Kravis and Blackstone have invested in technology firms before — most recently, Kohlberg bought the — private equity has rarely approached a firm as steeped in the arcana of technology as Cadence. Another question that faces Cadence's would-be buyers is its rich valuation. The company, based in San Jose, Calif., has a market value of about $6.4 billion, making it an expensive bet. Founded in 1983, Cadence has since become one of the largest makers of chip design software, partly through a string of acquisitions. Since 2004, it has bought four companies, including the software developer Verisity in a $315 million deal. It has also invested heavily in other Silicon Valley companies. And in 2006 it spent $1 billion in stock buybacks. Cadence is also regarded as one of the most innovative chip software makers. This year the company said that it would introduce a new approach to chip-making design, one that lays wires diagonally as well as horizontally and vertically. The new process would make its designs faster and more efficient, the company has said. Yet even that poses a dilemma for private equity. In such a highly technical field, research and development is crucial to establishing dominance, which requires large amounts of spending. And companies like Cadence and its largest rivals, and Synopsis, must innovate quickly as the pace of chip making accelerates. Cadence has already lost support from , the biggest name in microchips, which has invested in , a smaller rival which Intel said had the time-to-market advantage. Sphere: Related Blogs & Articles Next Article in Technology (3 of 23) &#x00bb; Need NEWS; CADENCE DESIGN TO BUY SIMPLEX FOR $300 MILLION Technology Briefing | Software: Mentor Graphics Wins a Round Criminal Charges Against Avant Dismissed AVANT TO BUY TECHNOLOGY MODELING FOR $150 MILLION Cadence Design Systems Incorporated Mergers, Acquisitions and Divestitures Next Article in Technology (3 of 23) &#x00bb; Follow the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuchee Bluegrass Festival? Tell him where to go in Tennessee and Kentucky Akeem Olajuwon - 1983 Media & Advertising &#x00bb; The Lede: Paris Hilton Reports to Prison ‘Grey Gardens’ Provides the Role of a Life Home Fires: Iraq Veterans Return All of a Sudden, the Weather Is Controversial The New York Times Company
http://www.nytimes.com/2007/06/04/technology/04marley.html Tiny Bit of Hardware With Marley Software - New York Times Tiny Bit of Hardware With Marley Software ANDREW ADAM NEWMAN Published: June 4, 2007 When reggae singer Bob Marley released “Exodus” in 1977, fans most likely bought it as a vinyl record, then over the decades went on to purchase it on CD or to download it. But those same boomers now can buy the album in a format that will impress even their computer-using children: on a U.S.B. flash drive. Skip to next paragraph Adrian Boot/Fifty-Six Hope Road Music The 30th anniversary release of Bob Marley&#146;s &#147;Exodus&#148; will also come on U.S.B. flash drives. For the 30th anniversary of “Exodus,” which Time magazine called the best album of the 20th Century, Island Records, a subsidiary of the Universal Music Group, produced 4,000 of the gizmos, which are loaded not only with the original 10 songs but also with additional tracks and concert video footage of Marley, who died in 1981. The memory sticks, which plug in to a computer’s U.S.B. ports, will be priced at $44.99. The high price reflects not only the extra content on the memory stick, but also the fact that the stick itself can be reused for other purposes. U.S.B. flash drives are generally sold empty, for the purpose of transferring data from one computer to another, but with the Bob Marley U.S.B. stick — as with others that store music — the entertainment can be downloaded to a computer and the device wiped clean. While the flash-drive format appears unlikely to reshape the recording industry anytime soon, a few bands are experimenting with it. Last year the Canadian band the Barenaked Ladies released its album “The Barenaked Ladies Are Me” on U.S.B. sticks along with CDs. So far the memory-stick version, at $25, has sold nearly 1,000 copies in North America, compared with 166,000 CDs, which cost $18.98. “By no means is it overtaking the traditionalists, but it’s a good start,” said Adam Smith, who manages artists at the Nettwerk Music Group, the band’s Canadian label. On recent tours, the Barenaked Ladies have been recording live performances and making them available on U.S.B. sticks at concert sites right after the last song is played. So far the band has sold about 3,000, for $40 each. That is more expensive than a CD, but buying music on a flash drive is akin to buying a Big Mac on a piece of Fiestaware. Mr. Smith pointed out that, unlike CDs, once the songs on a flash drive are transferred to a computer, they can be erased from the device, which can then be used to store data. Some flash drives sell for more than $30. “Once you upload the music to your computer, you have a piece of hardware,” Mr. Smith said. “If you’re buying a U.S.B. stick, the cost is not so much different to buy it loaded with music from your favorite band.” ANDREW ADAM NEWMAN Sphere: Related Blogs & Articles Next Article in Technology (12 of 23) &#x00bb; Need and the Internet Next Article in Technology (12 of 23) &#x00bb; Follow the Frugal Traveler on his 12-week cross-country journey See how the trip began What did he think of the Armuchee Bluegrass Festival? Tell him where to go in Tennessee and Kentucky Forever Fab Beatles Commemorative Media & Advertising &#x00bb; The Lede: Paris Hilton Reports to Prison ‘Grey Gardens’ Provides the Role of a Life Home Fires: Iraq Veterans Return All of a Sudden, the Weather Is Controversial The New York Times Company
